{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a5f8b725-ba21-482a-9908-4868cb86bb6c","content":"You're on MSTest 3.8.2, which supports constructor injection. Here's the recommended pattern:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncInitialization, IAsyncCleanup\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n\n    // Synchronous init via constructor injection\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // sync setup here\n    }\n\n    // Async init (replaces [TestInitialize] for async work)\n    public Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // await async setup here\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    // Async cleanup (replaces [TestCleanup] for async work)\n    public Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        return Task.CompletedTask;\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public void ExampleTest()\n    {\n        Assert.IsNotNull(_testContext);\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` replaces the property setter pattern.\n- **`IAsyncInitialization`** – implement for async per-test setup (runs after constructor).\n- **`IAsyncCleanup`** – implement for async per-test teardown.\n- You can still use `[ClassInitialize]`/`[ClassCleanup]` for one-time class-level setup if needed.\n- No `[TestInitialize]` attribute is needed when using the interface approach.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c4747468-5079-4138-b9b8-5c04f0418a3e","outputTokens":359,"requestId":"BD16:2A497:1DD9818:21C46D3:6A07CBB5"},"id":"b6841f0e-6205-4e2c-afb5-e7f09ea0f016","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:43:25.167Z","parentId":"214ccbd2-6011-4a6c-bca1-280fe840dc16"}
